This is "functional food" in America; many varieties that grow in Mexico correspond to climatic conditions [7]. The ancient inhabitants of Mexico, including the Aztecs and other natives, believed that the shape of the fruit corresponded to its properties [8]. Therefore, eating avocados contributed to strength and courage. Spanish colonial documentation The 16th century on the use of Native American medicinal plants confirms this connection, noting the fruit's reputation as an aphrodisiac, as well as its tendency to aid childbirth and reduce inflammation and indigestion. The avocado probably also had cultural significance to the Maya, who believed in the rebirth of their ancestors. as trees and therefore were known to surround their homes with fruit trees, including avocados[9].